<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="8120b760-9744-5f7e-b472-9a86a3f57d94" activityNameId="d725fb9c-3fa2-5190-9eda-0ede895196bc" parentActivityId="39a0ada1-4de3-5959-9928-35d37b78d2f4" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">sodium hydrogen sulfate production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">7681-38-1</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Fanal</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Bisulfate of soda</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">SODIUM BISULFATE</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Sodium acid sulfate</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Sodium hydrogen sulfate</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of sodium hydrogen sulfate (NaHSO4), also known as sodium bisulfate. In anydrous form, sodium hydrogen sulfate is a dry, granular product which can easily be transported and stored in bulk. NaHSO4 is the sodium salt of the bisulfate anion. The acid salt is formed by formed when partially neutralizing sulfuric acid with a sodium base, commonly sodium hydroxide or sodium chloride. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">A main function of sodium hydrogen sulfate is to lower pH. It is applied in metal finishing, jewelry making, cleaning products, textile industry and agriculture. A common application is also as food additive, for example to make cake mixes rise, process poultry or prevent fresh produce from browning. It is also often found in beverages, dressings, sauces and fillings and considered as natural by the food industry, as it is produced from minerals. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Reference(s): RÖMPP online. 2014. Natriumhydrogensulfat. Retrieved online from:  https://roempp.thieme.de/roempp4.0/do/data/RD-14-00415?update=true, 18 July 2017.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">For more information on the model please refer to the dedicate ecoinvent report, access it in the Report section of ecoQuery (http://www.ecoinvent.org/login-databases.html)</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="34dbbff8-88ce-11de-ad60-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">GLO</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inputs to the process are calculated based on stoichiometry and literature data, they are therefore considered to be valid for the chosen geography. The inputs of heat, electricity, water, factory and nitrogen are mostly taken as average of industry data. Industry data values are a 5-year average of data (2011 - 2015) published by the Gendorf factory (Gendorf, 2016, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de), (Gendorf, 2015, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de), (Gendorf, 2014, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de). The Gendorf factory is based in Germany, it produces a wide range of chemical substances. The factory produced 1657400 tonnes of chemical substances in the year 2015 (Gendorf, 2016, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de) and 740000 tonnes of intermediate products. Given the range of chemicals produced by the german site, the values are used for the GLO geography, with uncertainty adjusted accordingly.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Sodium Hydrogen Sulfate (HNaO4S) is here produced by the reaction of sodium hydroxide with sulfuric acid. Chemical reaction formula: HNaO + H2O4S → HNaO4S + H20</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">A process efficiency of 95% is assumed. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Another production route comprises the reaction of sodium chloride with sodium hydroxide at elevated temperatures to form sodium hydrogen sulfate and hydrogen chloride.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Reference(s): RÖMPP online. 2014. Natriumhydrogensulfat. Retrieved online from:  https://roempp.thieme.de/roempp4.0/do/data/RD-14-00415?update=true, 18 July 2017.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2015-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The activity is based on stoichiometry and literature data, it is therefore considered not to change significantly over time in terms of inputs.  The inputs of heat, electricity, water, factory and nitrogen are mostly taken as average of industry data. Industry data values are a 5-year average of data (2011 - 2015) published by the Gendorf factory (Gendorf, 2016, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de), (Gendorf, 2015, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de), (Gendorf, 2014, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de). The Gendorf factory is based in Germany, it produces a wide range of chemical substances. The factory produced 1657400 tonnes of chemical substances in the year 2015 (Gendorf, 2016, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de) and 740000 tonnes of intermediate products. The time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="b715e011-5294-5d02-9242-1bba0a6e4bd2" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" variableName="RP" casNumber="007681-38-1" amount="1.0" intermediateExchangeId="4f7d61bf-7489-5f91-9a40-cf8a849d3103" productionVolumeAmount="96000000.0" productionVolumeVariableName="RP_PV">
        <name xml:lang="en">sodium hydrogen sulfate</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Sodium hydrogen sulfate (NaHSO4), also known as sodium bisulfate. In anydrous form, sodium hydrogen sulfate is a dry, granular product which can easily be transported and stored in bulk. NaHSO4 is the sodium salt of the bisulfate anion. The acid salt is formed by formed when partially neutralizing sulfuric acid with a sodium base, commonly sodium hydroxide or sodium chloride. 
A main function of sodium hydrogen sulfate is to lower pH. It is applied in metal finishing, jewelry making, cleaning products, textile industry and agriculture. A common application is also as food additive, for example to make cake mixes rise, process poultry or prevent fresh produce from browning. It is also often found in beverages, dressings, sauces and fillings and considered as natural by the food industry, as it is produced from minerals. 

Reference(s): RÖMPP online. 2014. Natriumhydrogensulfat. Retrieved online from:  https://roempp.thieme.de/roempp4.0/do/data/RD-14-00415?update=true, 18 July 2017.</comment>
